						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biodiversity/Related-developments/Crop-biodiversity-going-up-not-down" title="Crop biodiversity going up, not down" alt="link">Crop biodiversity going up, not down</a></h2>

	
					<p>The decrease in biodiversity in the natural environment must lead to a decrease in the genetic variety of breeds among plant breeding companies. That would seem logical, but it is not the case. The genetic diversity in new breeds at plant breeding firms has increased slightly over the past few decades, after a fall in the 1960s. This is reported by researchers at the Dutch Centre for Genetic Resources (CGN) in the April edition of Theoretical and Applied Genetics. Mark van de Wouw of the CGN evaluated 44 publications in which the genetic diversity of crop varieties was studied with the help of genetic marker technology. (Source: Wageningen UR, 15 April 2010)</p>
							<p><span class="date">21/05/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biodiversity/Related-developments/Crop-biodiversity-going-up-not-down">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biodiversity/Related-developments/Genetic-diversity-in-farm-animals" title="Genetic diversity in farm animals" alt="link">Genetic diversity in farm animals</a></h2>

	
					<p>By International Foundation for Animal Genetics, 28 October 2009. The domestication of livestock species and a long history of migrations, selection and adaptation have created an enormous variety of breeds. Conservation of these genetic resources relies on demographic characterization, the recording of production environments and effective data management. In addition, molecular genetic studies allow a comparison of genetic diversity within and across breeds, and a reconstruction of the history of breeds and ancestral populations. This has been summarized for cattle, yak, water buffalo, sheep, goats, camelids, pigs, horses, and chickens. Further progress is expected to benefit from advances in molecular technology.</p>
							<p><span class="date">21/05/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biodiversity/Related-developments/Genetic-diversity-in-farm-animals">Read more...</a>
</div>
